# n8n Workflow Naming Convention

## Environments

All workflows exist in two environments within a **single n8n instance**:

| Environment | Purpose | Workflow Name Suffix | `active` |
|-------------|---------|---------------------|----------|
| **Development** | Testing, experiments, aggressive changes | `[DEV]` | `false` |
| **Production** | Stable, live workflows | (none) | `true` |

**Why single instance works:**
- Each workflow is unique (different name, different ID)
- Dev and prod use different credentials
- Different webhook URLs per workflow
- Dev workflow issues do NOT affect prod workflows

## Terminology

| Term | Where it shows | Format |
|------|----------------|--------|
| **Filename** | File explorer / disk | `{company}-{short-description}.json` |
| **Workflow name (Dev)** | Inside JSON `"name"` field / n8n UI | `{COMPANY} \| {Category} \| {short-description} [DEV]` |
| **Workflow name (Prod)** | Inside JSON `"name"` field / n8n UI | `{COMPANY} \| {Category} \| {short-description}` |

## Filename Format

All workflow JSON files should be named using this pattern:

```
{company}-{short-description}.json
```

Example: `tner-auto-fix-reconciliation.json`

**Same filename** is used in both `dev/` and `prod/` folders. The environment is determined by the folder, not the filename.

## Workflow Name Format

### Development Workflows
```
{COMPANY} | {Category} | {short-description} [DEV]
```
Example: `TNER | Admin | auto-fix-reconciliation [DEV]`

### Production Workflows
```
{COMPANY} | {Category} | {short-description}
```
Example: `TNER | Admin | auto-fix-reconciliation`

